_From @jsiedentop on November 23, 2016 18:59_

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Open the hello_service example in IntelliJ: `file -> open -> /flutter/examples/hello_services/`
2. Set a breakpoint (for example in line 66 inside of `main()`)
3. Start debugging: `run -> debug`
4. The example app start on the android device, but doesn't stop at breakpoints.

comment_data.body:
_From @eseidelGoogle on November 24, 2016 4:41_

Thanks for the report.
@jsiedentop what version of the Flutter IJ plugin do you have? (Settings/Preferences -> Plugins -> Flutter)

@jsiedentop I think this may be related to https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/466 (and noted your comment that you are on the latest plugin there).

Can you try to see if the following workaround makes it work?

1. Close any open projects you have in IJ with `hello_services` in them
1. Invoke File > New> Project... in IJ
1. Click Next on the Flutter SDK page
1. In the New Project screen, click the `...` button next to Project location, and browse to the folder that has the `hello_services` project
1. Click Finish
1. Say yes when it asks if you want to override an existing .idea or .idl files
1. Now add breakpoint and start Run > Debug

Note that hello_services is typically run differently than simpler flutter apps.  We haven't yet taught `flutter build` and `flutter run` about gradle so you have to call it directly to build the additional custom java code hello_services depends on:
https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/examples/hello_services/README.md
@pq did you have a chance to look at this?
Sorry for the slow reply.  I'm in flight and no android device handy.  Maybe @devoncarew can try and repro?  Otherwise, I can try when I'm back in the office on Friday.
We need to verify whether this is a bug or some feature work.

As per our conversation, this looks like feature work that should be coordinated with the work being done in AAR.

cc @mit-mit

Just repro-ing this now - I am able to debug the hello_services project with the flutter plugin. I:

- opened the examples/hello_service project in IntelliJ
- opened the iOS simulator
- set a breakpoint at line 59 (in setState(), `_latitude = reply...`)
- hit the 'debug' icon in the toolbar with the `hello_services` flutter launch config selected
- hit the 'locate' button in the app
- the breakpoint did fire and I could debug

I'm going to close this, but we'll keep an eye on the hello_service project as the interop work progresses.
